\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here I shall describe the problem, in a quite political thriller fashion.
 This is basically because of the dream I had.
 But not very much so.
 It involves some conspiracy theory, or should involve some.
 A british Air Force adjutant in NATO, while having the time of his life
 in general, and leading the normal life of a bachelor in his early forties,
 accidentally (runs back to the office to retrieve his keys and a bottle
 of fine scotch as a present to enjoy with his freshly picked love interest
 for the night, week or month) catches a burglar in the act of ransacking
 the hard drives of the office - need to find a good office for this or
 something that could genuinely have such data.
 Anyway, a small hunt ensues involving the underground train etc.
 Now, why would the main character try to get the burglar himself, instead
 of just calling security, the police, the military police and generally
 let someone else handle the matter? That's because the burglar is none
 other than his brother, who was trying to gather evidence and information
 on the money running between britain and the other NATO members, concerning
 military affairs and the procurement of equipment.
 Generally his brother was trying to expose another link in the scam-plan
 of the UN under the hospices of the Rothschilds' to reign supreme over
 all nations, managing their economies, incurring debts to everyone and
 effectively controling everyone on the planet.
 The underlying data would simply prove that the largest amount of money
 for the equipment is actually money that effectively goes straight in the
 Rothschilds' banks, and governments around the world simply need to buy
 something like military equipment to make it so expensive but somehow make
 it less irksome to the public to spend such inordinate amounts of money.
 When the officer finally catches up to his brother, he tries to present
 him with the truth of things, but the RAF man will have none of it, adhering
 to his sense of duty superficially, but simply fearing for his (and his
 brother's) life should they go on with something like trying to expose
 something that will stir global trouble.
 So he turns his brother in, and while actually awaiting for some sort of
 promotion or similar treatment, he gets transferred to Afghanistan as a
 liaison, with the intended purpose of staging an accident and doing away
 with him.
 The people behind this are in the payroll of the Rothschild's, without
 knowing who they work for.
 Instead they receive their orders from the same channels as everyone else,
 be they government officials or intelligence people.
 They are selected for their loyalty to money and greed foremost of everything
 else.
 While the RAF officer is on transit to Afghanistan, his brother is miraculously
 saved from a certain other accident through the intervention of a matrix-like
 hacktivist group that guides and helps him through anonymous people (something
 like Friends of Anonymous).
 He discovers that his life is in danger and tries to clear his digital
 presence, as well as mask his appearance in more traditional ways.
 He comes into contact with an 80-year old man, someone from the founding
 members of the friends, someone who knows a lot about the global situation
 and conflict, material and spiritual.
 He offers the man what he seeks, information, the way to absolution, redemption
 for everyone, saving the people of the world; the key is hidden in Mount
 Athos.
 He sends him there to meet with a wise father, a not so traditional type
 of hermit (but a hermit nonetheless) who, the old man promises him, has
 all the answers.
 Of course the orthodox hermit, has no inkling of the friends of anonymous,
 or such a concept, and simply is a christian to the heart and bone.
 This will be the main development in Part II, the british hacktivist turning
 into a solid orthodox christian, pledging to carry the word of God to its
 fulfillment and actuality.
 While this develops, the RAF officer is having second thoughts about his
 brother and his own actions.
 While on a routine cargo mission, he is guided to find while in-flight
 that there's a hardware error that would drive the plane smack on a mountain
 (altitude radar/GPS/INS/everything all at once).
 This leads him to believe someone's out to get him in fear of a leak (why
 kill him and not discredit him? because he was an officer with exemplary
 track record so far and no political ties, no dirt on him other than an
 active sex life - plus his brother was one loose end that someone failed
 to tie up).
 He jumps off the plane near a mountainous area controlled by the taliban.
 The co-pilot's chute fails to open, and his navigator is thrown against
 sheer cliff rocks.
 He is the only one to survive, but a bad fall and a tree make it difficult,
 and he is found by the taliban passed out.
 They decide to keep him restrained until a decision among them is reached:
 some want to send him away forcefully and return him, others to shoot him
 and be done with it.
 An elder notices a charm he wore, a charm that he had bought on a vacation
 to Greece; a meander.
 He proposes that since luck or Allah divined that he should live while
 his comrades died, and that he's wearing such a charm, that he's not for
 them to decide, but for the Kalash, who rever such people and are good
 friends, and sympathetic to all.
 He is led to Northern Pakistan and left in the care of a kalash village,
 where he too will have an epiphany in part II, that will lead him through
 a mountain trail to the Himalayas, where he will find the real key for
 the solution to mankind's problems (incredible machine - proof of evil's
 existence? - unlimited resources, energy? - gateway to original seeding
 planet of humanity? what is it that will deliver us? will it be a deus
 ex machina - or our own deliberate work from the ground up?).
